  "text": "where d\u00f0p j ; B\u00de \u00bc p j when p j 2 B 0 when p j ;B; & and B is the set over which the sum is taken [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Note that p i can be equal to the permanent environmental effect of other subjects with nonnull prior probability; this has an implication in the construction of conditional posterior distributions. Representation (19) illustrates that the conditional prior distribution of any of the permanent effects, given all other p's, is a mixture of C \u00c0 1 degenerate distributions (d\u00f0p j ; B\u00de) with point masses at p j \u00f0 j 6 \u00bc i\u00de and of the parametric base distribution N \u00f00; s 2 p \u00de. The mixing probabilities of states j 6 \u00bc i are 1=\u00f0M 1 C \u00c0 1\u00de for each of the C \u00c0 1 ''conditioning'' states, and M =\u00f0M 1 C \u00c0 1\u00de for the probability that p i is a draw from the normal process.",
